events.summary: Franz Liszt made his grand entry into the world while the Kingdom of Hungary was still figuring out what a piano was. Born on October 22, 1811, in Doborján, he was destined to become a musical genius, though at this point he was just a small bundle of potential.
At the tender age of nine, Liszt made his debut performance in Sopron, which had the audience convinced he was a child prodigy rather than just a remarkable distraction for a Saturday night.
After a successful debut, Liszt attracted a group of wealthy patrons to sponsor his education in Vienna, because what better way to learn music than on someone else's dime?

Liszt's debut concert in Vienna on December 1, 1822, made waves as he mingled with the aristocracy and probably left more than a few people wondering if they were in the presence of a future genius or just very bad luck.
Liszt staged his only opera, Don Sanche, which was enthusiastically received but ran for a mere four performances, leading him to realize maybe he should stick to the piano.

The tragic passing of Liszt's father in 1827 meant Liszt had to step up, leading him to give lessons all around Paris and also contemplate his life choices over a good bottle of wine—because who needs stability?
Rumor has it that Beethoven kissed Liszt on the forehead at a concert—it's a heartwarming story unless you're thinking about how awkward that must have been for the people watching.

Liszt struck up a relationship with the Countess Marie d'Agoult in 1833, because clearly, he was as good at falling in love as he was at playing the piano, resulting in both beautiful music and a couple of children.
Following his illustrious career, Liszt was bombarded by fans in a frenzy of 'Lisztomania'—as if he were a rock star, minus the electric guitars and leather pants.
In 1844, Liszt and Marie d'Agoult decided that maybe living together wasn't as glamorous as it sounded, leading to a split that let Liszt focus more on music and less on melodrama.
Throughout his life, Liszt taught piano to hundreds of students, essentially inventing the masterclass format, ensuring that the circle of piano misery continued for generations to come.

After separating from Marie, Liszt embarked on a concert spree that made fans go wild—think rockstar frenzy! His charisma on stage had women in Berlin fighting for his cigar butts and coffee remnants, turning concerts into theatrical battles of affection.

In a plot twist worthy of a soap opera, Liszt decided to retire at the ripe age of 35 while still dazzling audiences. It was like he left the stage while the crowd was still clamoring for more, keeping his legend untarnished.

Liszt moved to Weimar where he transformed into the court's music magician. Imagine him waving a conductor's baton while juggling the duties of a kapellmeister and plotting musical festivals. It was like a musical episode of 'The Office' at the court!

Liszt unknowingly became the head of a musical clique called the New German School. With flamboyant friends like Wagner and Berlioz, they challenged music norms like teenage rebels, all while exchanging heated debates in essays instead of punches.

After a long romantic saga that would make Shakespeare blush, Liszt and Carolyne finally thought they could tie the knot in Rome, only to be blocked by a Vatican official. Turns out love also needed a permission slip!

In a grand display of national pride, Liszt composed a special piece for the Hungarian coronation, proving that even in music, he knew how to throw a royal shindig. The church bells must have rung like they were announcing a concert!

Liszt returned to Budapest as a celebrated professor, teaching young musicians with the same flair he brought to his performances. It was like Hogwarts but for aspiring pianists—complete with magical music lessons!

In a dramatic finale, Liszt spent his last days supporting his daughter's festival. He was a true family man, championing Wagner’s works until the very end. Even illness couldn't overshadow the maestro's spirit as he waved his last baton.

Liszt and Chopin crossed paths in artistic circles, leading to a memorable first performance by Chopin that Liszt admired greatly. Who knew that admiration could spark a friendship filled with flamboyant personalities and charity concerts?

After a stellar introduction, Liszt and Chopin became close friends and performed together multiple times. It was almost a buddy comedy, with one being a piano hero and the other trying to hide from the limelight!
As years rolled on, the friendship cooled, with romantic entanglements and jealousy getting in the way. Who knew that artists could be so dramatic off-stage too?
Right after the news of Chopin's passing, Liszt jumped into action with a monument and a biography. Talk about being a friend who wants to be remembered—preferably in a flattering light!
Liszt's positive review of Schumann's works led to a correspondence and a meeting. Who knew a little praise could spark a friendship, although it was one rife with drama later on?

events.event: Performance in Honor of the Schumanns
events.summary: Two hours late to a piano trio performance honoring him, Liszt caused quite the stir. Speaking ill of Mendelssohn at a friendly gathering? That was one way to be uninvited from future events!
A heroic moment! Liszt offered Wagner refuge after a failed uprising, complete with a false passport and loan. Let’s call it 'friendship under fire'!
Arranging the premiere of Wagner's Lohengrin, Liszt showed off his dedication to friendship. It's like saying, 'I’ll help you out—even if it draws the ire of critics!'
Over a decade of supporting Wagner financially, Liszt proved to be the friend who really had your back—at least until the money ran out!
When Liszt found out Wagner was dating his daughter, it was like a plot twist in a soap opera, leaving him miffed and creating a rift—only to patch things up later in typical melodramatic fashion!
Liszt took his final bow during a Bayreuth Festival dedicated to Wagner's work. Talk about leaving the stage while passing the spotlight to his longtime friend—now that’s friendship goals!

Liszt blew everyone's minds in London by giving a solo piano recital, a concept so new that it made other performers feel like mere warm-up acts. The piano was so happy it nearly started singing itself!

After an epic brainstorming session in Paris, Liszt had his own 'piano-organ' built which could basically play both piano and harmonium. Because why settle for one when you can confuse the audience with two?

Liszt composed his two most significant organ masterpieces, proving that organ music could be as thrilling as a roller coaster ride, minus the nausea. His works have inspired many organists ever since, who are secretly competing to pull off the most dramatic performances.

With a cheeky pen stroke, Liszt defined program music, essentially saying, 'Let’s tell a story with music!' This concept made composers rush out to create musical narratives instead of just notes on a page.

Liszt decided that one-movement orchestral works should be a thing, creating what are now known as symphonic poems, allowing orchestras to stretch their storytelling muscles while still keeping their evening suits wrinkle-free.

Liszt embarked on a journey into more experimental music, writing quirky pieces that seemed to delight in keeping listeners guessing. They might have left scratching their heads, but at least it was never boring!

Liszt had his first public performance at the tender age of 9. While most kids were playing games, he was busy playing the piano like a seasoned pro, impressing everyone with his extraordinary talents.
Liszt began studying with Carl Czerny, who was not only a virtuoso in his own right but also had the uncanny ability to make years of musical practice feel like a fun roller coaster ride.

Liszt had a lightbulb moment when he decided that symphonic poems were the way to go. Suddenly, orchestras everywhere were writing pieces that told stories without any words—just lots of dramatic chords and melodies!
In a true tale of romance and bureaucracy, Liszt proposed to Princess Carolyne. However, their engagement was as tumultuous as any opera, filled with drama but alas, no wedding bells.
Liszt introduced the concept of the masterclass, where students learned by watching and listening. It was like a reality show, but with less drama and more piano.

Liszt gave his last public performance, leaving the audience in awe and disbelief that the music was coming to a close. It was as if the curtains were closing, but the echoes of his notes lingered in the air.

Liszt departed from this world, leaving behind a legacy of music that would make even the toughest critics soften. His final act might have been leaving the piano, but his music played on in the hearts of many.

At the tender age of six, little Franz began taking piano lessons from his father. It was a match made in music heaven, complete with relentless practice and occasional foot-stomping when the notes just wouldn't cooperate.

Young Liszt wowed the audience at his first public concert, proving that he was not just another child prodigy but a spectacular one. It's said the audience left wondering if they'd just seen a musical miracle or simply a young boy with a penchant for entertaining.

Liszt took Paris by storm, performing with such flair that he was quickly dubbed a piano superstar. There were tales of ladies fainting and gentlemen swooning, leaving debris of opera glasses and handkerchiefs in his wake.

Finding a love for the dramatic, Liszt wrote 'Totentanz'—a piece so intense that it could make a funeral feel like a lively party. Only Liszt could turn the theme of death into a virtuoso performance!

In a move to showcase composers' works beyond his own, Liszt hosted concerts featuring other musicians, proving he wasn’t just a piano hog. His self-sacrificing servant-heartedness was noted while simultaneously outshining everyone at the piano!
Liszt's Hungarian Rhapsodies hit the scene, blending national pride with musical fireworks. Suddenly, everyone wanted to dance their way through Hungary, even if they'd never left their living rooms!

At a tender age, Liszt performed his first concert and whisked his audience away on a musical journey so profound, it rivaled the most dramatic soap opera plot twists. Even the critics were left wondering how a child could produce such celestial sounds!

Liszt introduced revolutionary playing techniques that had pianists everywhere scrambling to keep up. He practically invented the 'Lisztian' style, making every performance feel like a thrilling rock concert but with more lace and less leather.

The premiere of his Piano Concerto No. 1 was met with such enthusiasm that it felt like a standing ovation was a mandatory response. People were so enchanted, they probably forgot there was a whole world outside the concert hall.

Liszt took on a legion of students, imparting his magical touch to the next generation of musicians. If his students weren't careful, they might have inadvertently created a whole new genre—'Liszt's Piano School of Rock'.
